\chapter{Households}
\label{chap:households} \index{households}
%#############################################################
\epigraph{There is nothing like staying at home for real comfort.}{Jane Austen}

Having developed a framework for sustainability thinking in Equation \ref{eq:IPARC}
and Chapters~\ref{chap:introduction}-\ref{chap:carbon_intensity},
this chapter is the first of four chapters to discuss
areas of life where sustainability challenges are relevant and important.
The four ``application areas'' are selected based, in part, on where energy
is used (Figure \ref{fig:LLNL_energy_sankey}), that is, where carbon emissions
originate (Table \ref{tab:corrected_co2_emissions}).
This chapter explores in implications and applications of sustainability thinking
to households.
Where and how you live \emph{might} be the area of your life over which you have 
the most control.
Transportation (Chapter~\ref{chap:transportation}), 
agriculture (Chapter~\ref{chap:agriculture}), and
land use and urban planning (Chapter~\ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning})
are the subjects of the next three chapters.
The structure of each chapter in Part \ref{part:sustainability_challenges} is similar:
First, the importance of that area of life to sustainability is discussed.
Next, technical details about sustainability in that area of life are presented.
Finally, a summary provides pointers to other chapters 
where personal or collective actions relevant to that area of life are discussed.

In this chapter, we begin by discussing
the importance of households for sustainability.
Thereafter, four areas of household sustainability are covered:
purchasing and renting, 
heating and cooling, 
hygiene, and 
lighting.
A summary concludes.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{The importance of households for sustainability}
\label{sec:households_sustainability_importance}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Households are important for sustainability, 
because they are sites of energy and material consumption.
For example, Figure~\ref{fig:LLNL_energy_sankey} shows that 
11.9~quads of energy are consumed in U.S.\ residences annually,
and Table~\ref{tab:corrected_co2_emissions} shows that CO$_2$ emissions
from the residential sector come to 
\Sexpr{US_CO2_by_sector$`CO$_2$ emissions [Mt]`[[1]] %>% round(0)}~Gt/year,
predominantly from electricity and natural gas.\index{electricity!consumption!households}
This 11.9~quads represents 12\% of final energy consumption.
Energy consumption is the source of sustainability impacts
(CO$_2$ emissions\index{carbon dioxide (CO$_2$)!emissions of} and 
natural resource extraction\index{natural resources!extraction of})
far beyond the site of the demand (households).
In addition to energy, sustainability impacts arise 
from household decisions about food\index{food!consumption of} and material consumption, too.
Thus, decisions made in households have sustainability implications
far beyond the walls of each abode.


%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Households are the site where sustainability meets everyday life.
\end{mcframe}

In the formal employment sector, 
physical plant employees, building managers, and custodial staff
make decisions about buildings and machines
that consume energy, raw materials, and other resources.
In contrast, ordinary people often have little power to make decisions
with sustainability implications
at work, at school, or at church.
However, everyone who lives in a house or apartment 
makes decisions with sustainability implications
in their home.

Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy} shows how the average U.S.\ resident
allocates energy consumption\index{energy consumption!residential}
for several end uses~\citep[Fig.~3]{EIA_2018}.
The end use categories in Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy} illustrate
how choices made in households
intersect with sustainability topics covered in other chapters, including
energy (Chapter~\ref{chap:resource_intensity}) and 
food (Chapter~\ref{chap:agriculture}).
Population (Chapter~\ref{chap:population}),
the economy (Chapter~\ref{chap:affluence}),
land use and urban planning (Chapter~\ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning}),
government (Chapter~\ref{chap:government}), and
personal actions (Chapter~\ref{chap:personal_action})
also affect household sustainability.

