\section{Heating and cooling}
\label{sec:heating_and_cooling} \index{households!heating and cooling}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

In most locations,
daily and seasonal temperature variations are wide
compared to the range of temperatures required for human comfort.
Average daily temperature variations can be in the range of 13~\degC,
and seasonal variations can be on the order of 30~\degC.%
\footnote{
   Example temperature variations are for Grand Rapids, Michigan, USA
   from \url{http://www.experiencegr.com}~\cite{Experience-Grand-Rapids:vs}.
}
In contrast, the range of human comfort is between 20 and 23~\degC, 
depending on humidity and clothing, 
or only 3~\degC.

Residential heating and cooling reduces the temperature variation
inside a dwelling compared to the outdoors,
providing thermal comfort to the occupants, 
thereby enabling work, play, and entertainment.
As shown in Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy},
on average across the U.S.,
thermal comfort\index{thermal comfort}
is provided
by **** 36.6\% **** of all residential energy consumption.
Like all energy consumption,
energy consumption for heating and cooling has sustainability implications.
(See Chapter~\ref{chap:resource_intensity}.)
Greater efficiency can provide the same thermal comfort
with less energy consumed
Increased residential heating and cooling 
efficiency\index{efficiency!heating and cooling!residential}
(i.e, providing the same comfort with less energy) 
can be obtained
by improving the building envelope or
by improving the efficiency of furnaces and air conditioners.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Building envelope}
\label{sec:building_envelope} \index{building envelope}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

The building envelope consists of the roof, walls, windows, and base
of a dwelling.
The purpose of the envelope is to shield occupants from outside weather and
to maintain dry and comfortable conditions inside the dwelling.
The ideal building envelope would
eliminate both heat loss in the winter and heat gain in the summer via
perfect roof and wall insulation and
windows that neither conduct heat nor pass radiation.
But perfect insulation is not possible, and all windows conduct heat and
pass thermal radiation.
So furnaces\index{furnaces} and air conditioners\index{air conditioners}
replace the heat lost in winter and remove heat gained in the summer.

The effectiveness of roof and wall insulation\index{insulation}
is quantified by its R-value\index{R-value},
a measure of the resistance to heat transfer through the insulation material
quantified in units of hr-ft$^2$-\degF/BTU.
Higher R-values are better.
Large R-values are achieved with
thicker insulation constructed from low-thermal-conductivity materials.
The Energy Star program recommends levels of roof, wall, and
floor insulation~\cite{U.S.-Department-of-Energy:aa}.
In Northern US climates, R-values of 49--60 hr-ft$^2$-\degF/BTU are recommended.

Windows\index{windows} are an important part of any building's envelope.
They provide natural illumination while shielding occupants from weather.
Like walls and roofs, it is desirable that windows eliminate
heat loss in the winter and heat gain the summer.
However, windows are typically worse insulators than walls and roofs,
owing to thin glazing.

The insulative properties of windows are quantified by the U-Factor\index{U-factor}.
The U-Factor is the inverse of an R-value.
Typical U-Factors for windows are 0.2--1.2 BTU/hr-ft$^2$-\degF.
(Corresponding window R-values are 5--0.83 hr-ft$^2$-\degF/BTU.)
Lower U values are more insulative.
Heat gain from solar radiation is quantified by the
solar heat gain coefficient (SHGC)\index{solar heat gain coefficient},
the ratio of solar energy that enters the room to
solar energy incident upon the window.
SHGC values range from 0 to 1,
and lower SHGC values indicate better insulative properties.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Furnaces}
\label{sec:furnaces}\index{furnaces}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Furnaces provide space heating,
often from an out-of-the-way location in the dwelling (e.g., basement).
Furnaces convert a fuel 
(typically natural gas\index{natural gas} or heating oil\index{heating oil})
into heat by combustion.
The heat is delivered to the dwelling via circulating water or air.

Furnace efficiency\index{efficiency!furnaces} is quantified as
Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency~(AFUE)\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)},
the percentage of useful heat output
to fuel energy input,
accounting for transient effects during operation
across the year.
The maximum AFUE rating is 100\%.
Heat that leaves the home with the exhaust products serves to reduce AFUE.
AFUE is different from and lower than steady-state thermal efficiency.
The American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)
\index{American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)}
publishes Standard 103,
which specifies how AFUE is to be measured~\cite{ASHRAE:vk}.

All furnaces sold in the U.S.\ have an AFUE rating, and
a minimum AFUE rating of 80\% is required
for gas-fired furnaces.\index{furnaces!gas-fired}
**** Find a good-quality reference for minimum AFUE of 80\% in the U.S. ****
High-efficiency furnaces recover more heat from exhaust gases,
and some reach AFUE values of 98\% or higher.
A tradeoff exists between efficiency and initial cost.
Models with high AFUE are more expensive, initially,
but save money on fuel costs over time.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Air conditioners}
\label{sec:air_conditioners}\index{air conditioners}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Air conditioners cool and dehumidify indoor air
to provide thermal comfort\index{thermal comfort}
to building occupants.
Most air conditioners consume electricity to perform their cooling function. 
The energy efficiency of air conditioners\index{efficiency!air conditioners}
is quantified by the
Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio (SEER),\index{Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio (SEER)}
which is
the ratio of cooling provided (in BTU)
to electricity consumed (in W-hr) throughout the season.
Larger SEER values indicate higher efficiency.

As of 2015, U.S.\ air conditioners must adhere to regionally dependent efficiency standards.
In the southwest, a minimum SEER value of 14 BTU/W-hr is required.
In other parts of the U.S., a minimum SEER value of 13 BTU/W-hr is mandated.
